    "Let me analyze this reaction to identify the roles of reagents, solvent, and catalyst.\n\nThe reaction SMILES shows:\n- Reactants: C1CCOC1 (THF/tetrahydrofuran), CO (methanol), COC(=O)CCC[C@@H]1O[C@H](c2ccccc2)OC[C@H]1O (methyl ester of a carboxylic acid - this is the substrate), [K+] and [OH-] (potassium hydroxide)\n\n- Product: O=C(O)CCC[C@@H]1O[C@H](c2ccccc2)OC[C@H]1O (carboxylic acid - the hydrolyzed product)\n\nThe transformation is clearly a hydrolysis of a methyl ester (COC(=O) → O=C(O)), converting the methyl ester to a carboxylic acid.\n\nNow let me identify the roles:\n1. **Substrate/Reactant**: COC(=O)CCC[C@@H]1O[C@H](c2ccccc2)OC[C@H]1O - the methyl ester being hydrolyzed\n2. **Reagent**: [K+].[OH-] (KOH) - this is the base/reagent that drives the hydrolysis (saponification)\n3. **Solvent**: C1CCOC1 (THF) and CO (methanol) - these are solvents for the reaction. THF/MeOH is a common solvent mixture for base-mediated ester hydrolysis.\n\nSo the role mapping:\n- THF (C1CCOC1): Solvent\n- Methanol (CO): Solvent (co-solvent)\n- Methyl ester substrate: Reactant (substrate)\n- KOH ([K+].[OH-]): Reagent (base for hydrolysis)\n\nThere is no catalyst in this reaction - KOH is a reagent, not a catalyst, as it is consumed in stoichiometric amounts during saponification.\n\nLet me format this as a condition_role_mapping:\n\nReactant: COC(=O)CCC[C@@H]1O[C@H](c2ccccc2)OC[C@H]1O (methyl ester substrate)\nReagent: [K+].[OH-] (KOH - base for ester hydrolysis/saponification)\nSolvent: C1CCOC1 (THF), CO (methanol)\nCatalyst: None"
